               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                  <msItem class="#funerary.epitaph">
                     <p>Epitaph of Nigrio(s) Aequidicus (?)</p>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc ana="#tablet">
                     <supportDesc ana="metal.lead">
                        <support>
                           <p>
                              <seg type="material">lead</seg>
                              <seg type="type">broken tablet</seg>
                           </p>
                              <dimensions type="surface" unit="cm">
                                 <width>22</width>
                                 <height>23</height>
                                 <depth>0.2</depth>
                              </dimensions>
                        </support>
                        <condition ana="fragment.single">
                           <p>Dull, pliable lead, with some traces of a greenish blue at the back, perhaps suggesting a coppor alloy. The top left-hand corner has been broken off, a rectangle approximately ca. 6.0 by 7.5 cm., but the general size of the tablet can be projected. Small parts of the edges have been folded over the front surface. Six small holes puncture the object without loss to the text. The varying thickness of the tablet and contours of the back surface give the impression that holes have been patched at a later period with poured lead. Many letters are so worn they are difficult to read.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="10">
                           <p>The first line is roughly centred. The next four lines are well spaced out, with spare room at the right margin, but the words of the remaining lines run almost to the edge of the support. Interpuncts appear to have been used regularly between words within each line.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc ana="#protruding.molded">
                     <handNote>Letters in shallow relief without serifs, appear to have formed when the lead was originally poured. The first and third strokes of the N slope slightly to the right as they ascend. The bottom line seems to have been cast imperfectly or worn excessively, since the lowest parts of most letters do not remain.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote/>
                  </decoDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <summary>This lead inscription had entered Columbia's holdings by March 1901, although its prior provenance is unknown. The unusual medium and production technique (i.e. a lead funeral tablet with letters in relief), and lack of provenance for the object, suggests its creation as a kind of draft model, a counterfeit, or some other anomaly, cf. NY.NY.CU.Butl.L.424</summary>
                  <origin>
                     <origPlace type="location"/>
                     <origDate notBefore="-0100" notAfter="0001" cert="low">first century BCE</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance type="observed" subtype="recorded" notAfter="1901-03-31">
                     <ab>Recorded as being in the possession of the Latin department in the March, 1901 edition of the <bibl><ptr type="rest-of-bibl" target="#CU_Quarterly">Columbia University Quarterly</ptr>, pp.<biblScope type="pp">189</biblScope></bibl>.</ab>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance type="observed" notAfter="2011-09-01">
                     <ab>Identified in the Butler library collection no later than 1 September 2011.</ab>
                  </provenance>
               </history>
